  "eprint": {
    "title": "Improved Discrete Gaussian and Subgaussian Analysis for Lattice Cryptography",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Nicholas Genise",
        "email": "nicholasgenise@gmail",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Daniele Micciancio",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Chris Peikert",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Michael Walter",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Discrete Gaussian distributions over lattices are central to\nlattice-based cryptography, and to the computational and mathematical\naspects of lattices more broadly. The literature contains a wealth of\nuseful theorems about the behavior of discrete Gaussians under\nconvolutions and related operations. Yet despite their structural\nsimilarities, most of these theorems are formally incomparable, and\ntheir proofs tend to be monolithic and written nearly \"from\nscratch,'' making them unnecessarily hard to verify, understand, and\nextend.\n\nIn this work we present a modular framework for analyzing linear\noperations on discrete Gaussian distributions. The framework abstracts\naway the particulars of Gaussians, and usually reduces proofs to the\nchoice of appropriate linear transformations and elementary linear\nalgebra. To showcase the approach, we establish several general\nproperties of discrete Gaussians, and show how to obtain all prior\nconvolution theorems (along with some new ones) as straightforward\ncorollaries. As another application, we describe a self-reduction for\nLearning With Errors~(LWE) that uses a fixed number of samples to\ngenerate an unlimited number of additional ones (having somewhat\nlarger error). The distinguishing features of our reduction are its\nsimple analysis in our framework, and its exclusive use of discrete\nGaussians without any loss in parameters relative to a prior mixed\ndiscrete-and-continuous approach.\n\nAs a contribution of independent interest, for subgaussian random\nmatrices we prove a singular value concentration bound with explicitly\nstated constants, and we give tighter heuristics for specific\ndistributions that are commonly used for generating lattice\ntrapdoors. These bounds yield improvements in the concrete\nbit-security estimates for trapdoor lattice cryptosystems.",
    "keywords": [
      "Discrete Gaussians"
    ],
    "category": "Foundations",
    "publication_info": "Published elsewhere. Minor revision. PKC 2020",
    "last_updated": "2020-03-18",
